The implementation of `DistinguishedNamePredicate` (https://github.com/elastic/elasticsearch/blob/master/x-pack/plugin/security/src/main/java/org/elasticsearch/xpack/security/authc/support/UserRoleMapper.java#L161) doesn't take into consideration that the user might have a `null` DN (user property) when a role mapping that uses a wildcard or regexp is in use and would possibly apply on that user. When [evaluating the rule](https://github.com/elastic/elasticsearch/blob/master/x-pack/plugin/security/src/main/java/org/elasticsearch/xpack/security/authc/support/UserRoleMapper.java#L196), this causes an `NPE` in `org.apache.lucene.util.automaton.CharacterRunAutomaton`

This can be reproduced with a role mapping such as 
```
{
    "enabled" : true,
    "roles" : [
      "kibana_user"
    ],
    "rules" : {
      "field" : {
        "dn" : "*,ou=finance,dc=somethign,dc=com"
      }
    },
    "metadata" : { }
  }
```

and a i.e. SAML user in a realm that has no `attributes.dn` mapping rule in the configuration. The result is an uncaught NPE that causes the authentication to fail

`RetentionLeaseIT testCanRenewRetentionLeaseWithoutWaitingForShards` failed in https://elasticsearch-ci.elastic.co/job/elastic+elasticsearch+master+g1gc/565/console

The exception that caused the failure was:

```
java.lang.AssertionError: ElasticsearchException[java.io.IOException: failed to read /var/lib/jenkins/workspace/elastic+elasticsearch+master+g1gc/server/build/testrun/integTest/temp/org.elasticsearch.index.seqno.RetentionLeaseIT_C70B235D5835B1AE-001/tempDir-008/data/nodes/0/indices/3YlDl4joQjiLzNdRZJyHpg/0/_state/retention-leases-1.st]; nested: IOException[failed to read /var/lib/jenkins/workspace/elastic+elasticsearch+master+g1gc/server/build/testrun/integTest/temp/org.elasticsearch.index.seqno.RetentionLeaseIT_C70B235D5835B1AE-001/tempDir-008/data/nodes/0/indices/3YlDl4joQjiLzNdRZJyHpg/0/_state/retention-leases-1.st]; nested: NoSuchFileException[/var/lib/jenkins/workspace/elastic+elasticsearch+master+g1gc/server/build/testrun/integTest/temp/org.elasticsearch.index.seqno.RetentionLeaseIT_C70B235D5835B1AE-001/tempDir-008/data/nodes/0/indices/3YlDl4joQjiLzNdRZJyHpg/0/_state/retention-leases-1.st];
```

The full stack traces of those underlying failures are not available as the assertion that made the test fail was:

```
                    } catch (final Exception e) {
                        fail(e.toString());
                    }
```

The problem does not reproduce locally using:

```
./gradlew :server:integTest --tests "org.elasticsearch.index.seqno.RetentionLeaseIT.testCanRenewRetentionLeaseWithoutWaitingForShards" -Dtests.seed=C70B235D5835B1AE -Dtests.security.manager=true -Dtests.jvm.argline="-XX:-UseConcMarkSweepGC -XX:+UseG1GC" -Dtests.locale=ms-BN -Dtests.timezone=Europe/Vilnius -Dcompiler.java=12 -Druntime.java=11
```

**Elasticsearch version**: 7.0.0

**Plugins installed**: []

**JVM version**: OpenJDK 1.8.0_191

**OS version**: Ubuntu 16.04 (or Elastic Cloud)

**Description of the problem including expected versus actual behavior**:

When setting `_source.enabled: false` in the index mapping, the `_source` should not be stored.

In 7.0.0, when two indices have identical data and mappings (except for one having `_source.enabled: false`), the indices will be almost exactly the same size. This isn't the expected behavior.

In 6.7.1, when two indices with identical data and mappings (except for one having `source.enabled: false`), the index with `_source.enabled: false` is roughly half the size of the one with `_source` enabled. This is the expected behavior.

**Steps to reproduce**:

Overview:

1. Create two Elasticsearch clusters: version 6.7.1 and version 7.0.0.

2. Create two index templates with identical mappings, but let the second template use `_source.enabled: false`. Put these two index templates in both clusters.

3. Load data into the two indices on both clusters.

4. Force merge the indices to a single segment.

5. Compare the "Storage Size" of the two indices in Kibana for each cluster: `/app/kibana#/management/elasticsearch/index_management/indices`

